{
  "title": "Find Duplicate Elements in an Array using Hashing in C",
  "content": "</div><h2 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000; font-size: 18pt;\"><strong>Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C:</strong></span></h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">In this article, I am going to discuss <strong>Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language</strong> with Examples. In our previous article, we have seen <a href=\"#/course/dsa/finding-duplicates-in-a-sorted-array-in-c\"><strong>how to find duplicate elements in a sorted array</strong></a>.</span></p>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?</strong></span></h5>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">We have the following sorted array.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/7e22434939b860d50f6371a7283cc7c8.png\" fetchpriority=\"high\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22002\" title=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" alt=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" width=\"579\" height=\"107\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">We have taken a sorted array that has duplicated elements. As we can see elements reoccur one or more than one time in the above array. We want to know the duplicate elements as well as their count i.e. 13 is duplicated, then how many times it duplicated. For this, we are using a method that will use a hash table. As we have seen in the hash table in our previous articles. Below is the simplest form of hast table:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/6c97cc5e890eb6405228ef2aabe7274a.png\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22003\" title=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" alt=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" width=\"804\" height=\"94\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">We take the size of hast table 16 because 16 is the largest element in the above-given array. As we have taken a sorted array so we can find the largest element at the end of the array. Next, we have to fill the hash table or extra array with zeroes. Now, let’s look at the procedure:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">We have to scan through the given array by taking one element at a time.</span></p></div><h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>0<sup>th</sup> Index:</strong></span></h5>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">We are taking an index pointer ‘k’ which is starting from the 0<sup>th</sup> index:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22004\" title=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" alt=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" width=\"580\" height=\"139\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">k is at C [0] which is 5. So go to the extra array and increment the value of index 5:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22005\" title=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" alt=\"How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language?\" width=\"795\" height=\"93\"></span></p>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>1<sup>st</sup> Index:</strong></span></h5>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">Now, ‘k’ is pointing to the 1<sup>st</sup> index:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22006\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" width=\"580\" height=\"139\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">k is at C [1] which is 7. So go to the extra array and increment the value of index 7:</span></p></div><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22007\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" width=\"795\" height=\"93\"></span></p>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>2<sup>nd</sup> Index:</strong></span></h5>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">Now, ‘k’ is pointing to the 2<sup>nd</sup> index:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22008\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" width=\"580\" height=\"139\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">k is at C [2] which is 9. So go to the extra array and increment the value of index 9:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22009\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples\" width=\"795\" height=\"93\"></span></p>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>3<sup>rd</sup> Index:</strong></span></h5>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">Now, ‘k’ is pointing to the 3<sup>rd</sup> index:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22010\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" width=\"584\" height=\"140\"></span></p></div><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">k is at C [3] which is 9 again. In the extra array, increment the value of index 9:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22011\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" width=\"795\" height=\"93\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">In the same manner, we will trace the whole array and increment the value of the extra array as we will find duplicate elements. So, at last, our extra array will be:</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone wp-image-22012\" title=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" alt=\"Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language\" width=\"1346\" height=\"157\"></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">So, when we will find any duplicate element then we will increment the value of the same index number in the extra array ‘H’.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">Let’s do some analysis. So, how many times we are scanning through the array? Only 1 time. While scanning we are incrementing the count in the extra array. So, it will be constant time. The major time we spent is O (n). Now we have to find out what are the duplicate elements from the above hast table. So, we will scan for 1. For scanning the hash table, it will take O (n). Here n means linear.</span></p>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>Full Code in C language:</strong></span></h5>\n<pre class=\"EnlighterJSRAW\" data-enlighter-language=\"c\">#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;\r\n#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;\r\n\r\nstruct List{\r\n int C[15];\r\n int size;\r\n int length;\r\n};\r\n\r\nvoid Display(struct List list) {\r\n int i;\r\n printf(\"Elements are:\\n\");\r\n for (i = 0;i&lt;list.length;i++)\r\n  printf(\"%d \", list.C[i]);\r\n printf(\"\\n\\n\");\r\n}\r\n\r\nvoid DuplicateHashTable(struct List list, int max){\r\n \r\n int H[max+1];\r\n \r\n for(int i = 0; i &lt;= max; i++){\r\n     H[i] = 0;\r\n }\r\n \r\n for(int i = 0; i &lt; list.length; i++){\r\n  H[list.C[i]]++;\r\n }\r\n \r\n printf(\"Duplicate Elements are: \\n\");\r\n for (int i = 0; i &lt;= max; i++){\r\n  if(H[i] &gt; 1)\r\n   printf(\"%d is appearing: %d times\\n\", i, H[i]);\t\r\n }\r\n}\r\n\r\nint main(){\r\n struct List list_1 = {{5, 7, 9, 9, 10, 11, 13, 13, 13, 16}, 10, 10};\r\n \r\n Display(list_1);\r\n \r\n DuplicateHashTable(list_1, 16);\r\n}\r\n</pre>\n<h6 style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>Output:</strong></span></h6>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><img src=\"images/d0399b4bcb6a538ed241d2a282e410db.gif\" alt=\"blank\" onload=\"Wpfcll.r(this,true);\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"481\" height=\"194\" class=\"wp-image-22013\"></span></p></div><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">If we have a single for loop then time will be n and if we have for loop inside for loop then it will take n<sup>2</sup>.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\"><strong>Time Complexity: O(n)</strong></span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; color: #000000;\">In the next article, I am going to discuss <a href=\"#/course/dsa/finding-duplicate-elements-in-an-unsorted-array-in-c\"><strong>How to Find Duplicate Elements in an Unsorted Array in C Language</strong></a> with Examples. Here, in this article, I try to explain <strong>How to Find Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language </strong>with Examples and I hope you enjoy this Finding Duplicate Elements in a Sorted Array using Hashing in C Language with Examples article.</span></p>\n<div class=\"sabox-authors\"><div"
}